    type: "range",
    description: "High score means more healthy",
    info: `Test name: The Hopkins Verbal Learning Test. Score range: 20 to 80 (derived score). High score means more healthy. Purpose: The HVLT is used to assess a person's ability to learn and recall verbal information. Administration: The HVLT consists of three learning trials in which the person is presented with a list of 12 words and asked to recall as many words as possible immediately after each trial. After a 20-30 minute delay, the person is asked to recall the words again (delayed recall). Scoring: The HVLT produces several scores, including total immediate recall, delayed recall, and recognition discriminability. Norms: The HVLT has been standardized on a large sample of individuals, so scores can be compared to the norms for that person's age, education level, and other demographic factors. Advantages: The HVLT is a quick and easy assessment tool that can provide valuable information about a person's verbal learning and memory abilities. Limitations: The HVLT is a useful tool, but it is important to remember that it measures only one aspect of cognitive functioning (verbal learning and memory). It is also not a diagnostic tool on its own, but rather one part of a comprehensive neuropsychological evaluation. Overall, the Hopkins Verbal Learning Test is a valuable tool for assessing verbal learning and memory abilities, and can provide important information for diagnosing and treating cognitive disorders.`,
